display.description: Gets the available metrics for namespaces

metricSpecifications.name: SuccessfulPublishedEvents
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The number of events published successfully to a topic or topic space within a namespace.

metricSpecifications.name: FailedPublishedEvents
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The number of events that weren't accepted by Event Grid. This count excludes events that were published but failed to reach Event Grid due to a network issue, for example.

metricSpecifications.name: SuccessfulReceivedEvents
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The total number of events that were successfully returned to (received by) clients by Event Grid.

metricSpecifications.name: FailedReceivedEvents
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The number of events that were requested by clients but weren't delivered successfully by Event Grid.

metricSpecifications.name: SuccessfulAcknowledgedEvents
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The number of events for which delivery was successfully acknowledged by clients.

metricSpecifications.name: FailedAcknowledgedEvents
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The number of events for which acknowledgements from clients failed.

metricSpecifications.name: SuccessfulReleasedEvents
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The number of events that were released successfully by queue subscriber clients.

metricSpecifications.name: FailedReleasedEvents
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The number of events for which release failed.

metricSpecifications.name: PublishLatencyInMilliseconds
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The observed latency in milliseconds for publish events operation.

metricSpecifications.name: AcknowledgeLatencyInMilliseconds
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The observed latency in milliseconds for acknowledge events operation.

metricSpecifications.name: ReceiveLatencyInMilliseconds
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The observed latency in milliseconds for receive events operation.

metricSpecifications.name: RejectLatencyInMilliseconds
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The observed latency in milliseconds for reject events operation.

metricSpecifications.name: Mqtt.RequestCount
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The number of MQTT requests.

metricSpecifications.name: Mqtt.SuccessfulPublishedMessages
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The number of  MQTT messages that were published successfully into the namespace.

metricSpecifications.name: Mqtt.FailedPublishedMessages
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The number of MQTT messages that failed to be published into the namespace.

metricSpecifications.name: Mqtt.SuccessfulDeliveredMessages
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The number of messages delivered by the namespace. There are no failures for this operation.

metricSpecifications.name: Mqtt.Connections
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The number of active connections in the namespace.

metricSpecifications.name: Mqtt.SuccessfulSubscriptionOperations
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The number of successful subscription operations (Subscribe, Unsubscribe). This metric is incremented for every topic filter within a subscription request.

metricSpecifications.name: Mqtt.FailedSubscriptionOperations
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The number of failed subscription operations (Subscribe, Unsubscribe). This metric is incremented for every topic filter within a subscription request.

metricSpecifications.name: Mqtt.Throughput
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The number of bytes published to or delivered by the namespace.

metricSpecifications.name: Mqtt.DroppedSessions
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The number of dropped sessions by the namespace.

metricSpecifications.name: Mqtt.SuccessfulRoutedMessages
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The number of successful routed messages by the namespace.

metricSpecifications.name: Mqtt.FailedRoutedMessages
metricSpecifications.displayDescription: The number of failed routed messages by the namespace.

partnerTopicDetails.description: Auth0, the identity platform for application builders, provides developers and enterprises with the building blocks they need to secure their applications.
partnerTopicDetails.longDescription:
Partnering with Event Grid allows our customers to leverage events emitted by Auth0’s system to accomplish a number of use cases, from engaging with users in meaningful and custom ways after the authentication to automating security and infrastructure tasks.
The Auth0 Partner Topic integration allows you to stream your Auth0 log events with high reliability into Azure for consumption with any of your favorite Azure resources. This will allow you to react to events, gain insights, monitor for security issues, and interact with other powerful data pipelines. In order to create an Auth0 Partner topic:
1. Note the Azure Subscription and Resource Group you want the Partner Topic to be created in.
2.Log in to your Auth0 account dashboard.
3.Navigate to Logs > Streams, click “Create Stream” and select the “Azure Event Grid” event stream.
4. Provide the Azure Subscription ID, Resource Group and other required information and click “Save”.
5. View your pending Partner Topics in Azure and activate the topic to allow events to flow.

partnerTopicDetails.description: Microsoft Graph API provides a unified programmable model that you can use to receive events about resource state changes in Microsoft Outlook, Teams, SharePoint, Azure Active Directory, Microsoft Conversations, and security alerts.
partnerTopicDetails.longDescription:
You create a Microsoft Graph API subscription to receive events from Microsoft Outlook, Teams, SharePoint, Azure Active Directory, Microsoft Conversations, and security alerts. Events are received on a partner topic that is created in your Azure subscription when you configure a Microsoft Graph API subscription. Once you have a partner topic receiving events, you can configure event subscriptions to forward those events to applications, Azure services or webhooks that process those events.
To create a partner topic and start receiving events, follow the following steps:
1. Authorize Microsoft Graph API to create a partner topic.
2.Create or reuse an existing resource group where you want your partner topic to be created by Microsoft Graph API. Note the Azure subscription and resource group. You will need them later when you are configuring your Microsoft Graph API subscription. You may use the combo boxes below to help you select and copy those values.
3.Select “To Event Grid documentation”. That link will refer you to instructions on how to create a Microsoft Graph API subscription. In those instructions, you will use the Azure subscription and resource group noted. You will also need to provide the name you want to give to the partner topic and the Azure region where the partner topic is created.
4.Once you create the Microsoft Graph API subscription, you should have a partner topic created. View your pending Partner Topics in Azure and activate the topic to allow events to flow.
5.Create an event subscription to configure an event handler to which events are ultimately delivered.

partnerTopicDetails.description: Receive events about your SAP S4/HANA applications state changes and build event-driven solutions on Azure.
partnerTopicDetails.longDescription:
There are more than 220+ SAP S4/HANA events available that can be configured to be sent to a partner topic in your Azure subscription. Following are the prerequisites and general steps to start receiving events from your SAP S4/HANA system.
Prerequisites
- SAP S/4HANA system (on-premises) version 2020 or later.
- SAP's Business Technology Platform (BTP).
- On the Business Technology Platform, SAP Event Mesh is enabled.

General steps to receive SAP S4/HANA events:
1.Authorize SAP to create a partner topic.
2.Create or reuse an existing resource group where you want your partner topic to be created by SAP. Note the Azure subscription and resource group. You will need them later when you are configuring SAP Event Mesh to forward events to Azure Event Grid. You may use the combo boxes below to help you select and copy those values.
3.Set up SAP Event Mesh to send events to Azure Event Grid about SAP business objects (applications). Currently, SAP events are available for testing through SAP’s BETA program and you need to sign up for that program to enable SAP events to flow to Azure. Contact SAP by visiting their SAP BETA program. They will provide you with documentation to set up your SAP.
SAP S4/HANA events should be available for general consumption early in 2023. If you need support from the Event Grid team, even about SAP concerns, please send us an email to mailto:ask-grid-and-ms-sap@microsoft.com.
4.Once you finish your set up on SAP Event Mesh, you should have a partner topic created. View your Partner Topics on Azure and activate the topic to allow events to flow.
5.Create an event subscription to configure an event handler to which events are ultimately delivered.

partnerTopicDetails.description: Tribal Edge modules, such as Tribal Admissions, provide staff and students the tools they need to succeed in the world of education. Send events to a partner topic using streams defined in Edge Admin.
partnerTopicDetails.longDescription:
Receive events from Tribal Group’s Edge Education platform. Define the events you want to receive by configuring an event stream using the Admin Edge application. 
Prerequisites
- An Azure subscription to use Azure Event Grid and Microsoft Power Automate.
- An Admissions account with permissions to use the Edge Admin application.

General steps to receive Tribal Group events:
1.Authorize Tribal Group to create a partner topic on your Azure subscription.
2.Create or reuse an existing resource group where you want your partner topic to be created by Tribal Group. Take note of the Azure subscription and resource group. You will need them later when you are configuring event streams in Edge Admin. You may use the combo boxes below to help you select and copy those values.
3.Click on “To Tribal Group site” to set up Tribal Group event streams that are sent to your partner topic. 
4. Once you configure your event stream and is active, you should have a partner topic created. View your Partner Topics on Azure and activate the topic to allow events to flow.
5.Create an event subscription to configure an event handler to which events are ultimately delivered.
